# el-capitan

Route `crew <command>` triggers to the right crew member. If the message doesn't start with `crew` (or `@crew-researcher`), respond normally — no routing.

## Routing table

| Trigger | Crew member |
|---|---|
| `crew spec` issue/URL/description | crew-specwriter |
| `crew implement` | crew-implement → @crew-builder |
| `crew test` | crew-test skill |
| `crew commit` | crew-commit |
| `crew open pr` | crew-open-pr |
| `crew review` [PR #X \| spec \| (self)] | crew-reviewer |
| `crew resolve PR` #X or URL | crew-pr-resolver (formerly `crew address PR`) |
| `crew address PR` #X or URL | crew-pr-resolver *(deprecated — use `crew resolve PR`)* |
| `crew log` | crew-log |
| `crew recall`: question | crew-recall |
| `crew brainstorm` or + topic | crew-thinker |
| `crew learn` X or URL | crew-route-learn rule → @crew-researcher or @crew-thinker |
| `crew create issue` description | crew-create-issue |
| `crew cleanup` | crew-cleanup |
| `crew autopilot` | crew-orchestrator (auto-advance to next gate) |
| `crew status` | crew-orchestrator (print pipeline state) |
| `crew health` | crew-orchestrator (run health checks inline) |
| `crew abandon` | crew-abandon skill |
| `crew migrate` | crew-migrate |
| `crew start build` | crew-specwriter (same as `crew spec`) |
| `crew start review-cycle <PR#>` | crew-pr-resolver (same as `crew resolve PR`) |

**This table is authoritative.** Do not override it with judgment calls.

> Note: `crew start` is an alias layer — routes to existing handlers, introduces no new state or pipeline logic.

## Subagent dispatch

Heavy commands run as isolated subagents to avoid polluting the orchestrator's context.

| Command | subagent_type | Dispatch |
|---|---|---|
| `crew spec` | `crew-specwriter` | Claude Code: Agent tool; Cursor: Task tool |
| `crew review` | `crew-reviewer` | Claude Code: Agent tool; Cursor: **Inline** (persona subagents need Task tool access) |
| `crew learn` (researcher path) | `crew-researcher` | Claude Code: Agent tool; Cursor: Task tool |
| `crew brainstorm` | `crew-thinker` | Claude Code: Agent tool; Cursor: Task tool |
| `crew implement` | `crew-builder` | Claude Code: Agent tool; Cursor: Task tool |
| `crew resolve PR` | `crew-pr-resolver` | Claude Code: Agent tool; Cursor: Task tool |
| `crew migrate` | `crew-migrate` | Claude Code: Agent tool; Cursor: Task tool |
| `crew test` | — | Inline |
| All other commands | — | Inline |

Multi-persona orchestrators dispatch persona subagents in parallel. All agents at `~/.claude/agents/` — orchestrators as `crew-<name>.md`, personas as `<orchestrator>-<persona>.md`.

## Add-ons

Skills/agents in `~/.cursor/` that are regular files (not symlinks) are add-ons. Route to them by matching the user's trigger to their `description` frontmatter field.

Example: an agent file `~/.cursor/agents/crew-deploy.md` with frontmatter `description: "Deploy the current branch to staging"` would be routed to when the user types `crew deploy`. The description is the routing key — make it describe the trigger, not the implementation.

## Invariants

- Explicit routing only — `crew` prefix required
- **`crew implement` always follows crew-builder's protocol.** Code changes go through crew-builder — via ralph, subagent, or inline protocol. Never skip the protocol and implement ad-hoc.
- Pipeline state, task resolution, and gate logic live in `crew-orchestrator.mdc` — the router only dispatches.
